  "output": "## Codebase reality check\n\nThis is a pure Python job-scraping pipeline (fetchers → filter → dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React/frontend code anywhere in the repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I focused on the categories that do: N+1 query patterns, caching, memory, and redundant computation.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (`Store.diff`) — **highest impact**\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)          # separate INSERT per job\n    else:\n        ...\n        cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n```\n\nBoards like Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Workday routinely return 3,000-6,000+ listings per run, so this is one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE **per job**, in a Python loop — classic N+1. Fix: load existing `(key, content_hash)` pairs once, diff in memory, then batch-write with `executemany` inside a single transaction:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n\n    new, changed, seen_rows, touched = [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); seen_rows.append(row)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); touched.append(row)\n        else:\n            self.conn.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if seen_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key, ...)\", seen_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, ... WHERE key=:key\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round trips into O(1) reads + 2 batched writes.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:11-26` (regex recompiled per job)\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled EVERY call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job, and `match()` re-`re.compile()`s the same include/exclude word lists every single time — thousands of redundant compiles per run. Fix: compile once outside the loop and pass compiled patterns in:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation / wasted allocation — `models.py:71-75` (`Job.to_row`)\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # recursively DEEP-COPIES every nested dict/list, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)     # ...then immediately throws it away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively deep-copies nested structures. `raw` holds the full source payload (can be a sizable nested dict for Workday/Apple/Eightfold postings), and it gets deep-copied on every insert/update/webhook-notify call just to be discarded a line later. Fix: build the dict directly instead of going through `asdict`:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = {f: getattr(self, f) for f in\n         (\"source\", \"company\", \"external_id\", \"title\", \"url\", \"location\",\n          \"department\", \"employment_type\", \"posted_at\", \"salary_range\")}\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\nAlso note `store.diff()` computes `job.content_hash` once for the comparison, then `_insert`/`_update` → `to_row()` recomputes it again (a SHA-256 call) — cheap individually, but easy to avoid once you're already batching per fix #1 (compute it once per job and thread it through).\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — HTTP conditional requests (minor, optional)\n\n`_simple()` fetchers (Greenhouse, Lever, SmartRecruiters, Recruitee, Workable — `fetchers.py:763-770`) do a full unconditional `GET` every run even when a board hasn't changed. Since `Store.diff` already dedups by content hash, this doesn't cause correctness issues, but if run frequency increases (the repo already has a 12h cron per your commit history), adding `If-None-Match`/`ETag` handling would cut bandwidth and avoid needless JSON parsing on unchanged boards. Low priority — the boards are small enough (single JSON payload) that this isn't worth the complexity unless run frequency goes up significantly.\n\n### 5. Memory — no leaks found, one footprint note\n\n- `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all` (`fetchers.py:1126-1147`) is properly closed in a `finally`; `Store`/`smtplib.SMTP` connections use context managers correctly throughout.\n- Not a leak (process is one-shot per run), but worth knowing: every `Job` retains its full `raw` source payload for the run's lifetime (`models.py:52`), and large boards (Apple ~6,400 roles, Amazon/Microsoft thousands) will hold thousands of these dicts in memory simultaneously via `fetch_all`'s `asyncio.gather`. Not urgent, but if a run grows to cover many big boards at once, consider dropping `raw` after `to_row()`/notify use it, or making it optional per-fetcher only when actually needed downstream.\n\n### Priority order\n1. Fix the `store.diff` N+1 (biggest real win, straightforward).\n2. Hoist regex compilation out of the per-job filter loop.\n3. Replace `asdict()`-based `to_row()` to stop deep-copying `raw`.\n4. HTTP caching / raw-payload retention — nice-to-haves, not urgent at current scale.\n",
